%U A397341 137341723789313929643,137341723789313929643419,13734172378931392964341943,1373417237893139296434194329,137341723789313929643419432937,13734172378931392964341943293729
%N A397341 a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) is the concatenation of a(n-1) and the smallest prime p such that the concatenation a(n-1) | p is prime.
%C A397341 This sequence is similar to A158191, but starts with 1 instead of prime 2.
%C A397341 The corresponding sequence of appended primes are in A397342.
%C A397341 Conjecture: a(n) exists for all n. Equivalently, for every F >= 1, there is a prime p such that F*10^d(p) + p is prime.
%C A397341 For a fixed F and a k-digit prime p, the number F*10^k + p is roughly of size F*10^k, so the probability that it is prime is approximately 1/log(F*10^k) ≈ 1/(k log 10). Since there are about 10^k/k primes with k digits, the expected number of successes for a given k is about 10^k/k^2, which tends to infinity. Thus, the construction should never get stuck. This is consistent with the Bateman-Horn conjecture and Schinzel's Hypothesis H.
%C A397341 a(281) has 1005 digits. - _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 24 2026
%H A397341 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397341/b397341.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..280</a>
%H A397341 Mathematics Stack Exchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/5141344/a-recursive-prime-concatenation-process-does-it-always-admit-a-next-prime">A recursive prime-concatenation process: does it always admit a next prime?</a>
%F A397341 a(1) = 1; for n > 1, let p_{n-1} be the smallest prime such that a(n) = a(n-1) * 10^{d(p_{n-1})} + p_{n-1} is prime, where d(p) denotes the number of decimal digits of p.
%e A397341 a(1) = 1.
%e A397341 a(2) = 13 since 1|3 = 13 is prime (but 1|2 = 12 is not).
%e A397341 a(3) = 137 since 13|7 = 137 is prime (but 132, 133 and 135 are not).
%e A397341 a(4) = 1373 since 137|3 = 1373 is prime (but 137|2 = 1372 is not).
%t A397341 next[F_] := NestWhile[NextPrime, 2, ! PrimeQ[F*10^IntegerLength[#] + #] &];
%t A397341 F = 1; seq = {1};
%t A397341 Do[p = next[F]; F = F*10^IntegerLength[p] + p; AppendTo[seq, F], {20}];
%t A397341 seq
%o A397341 (Python)
%o A397341 import sympy as sp
%o A397341 def anext(term):
%o A397341     k = 1
%o A397341     while True:
%o A397341         for p in sp.primerange(10**(k-1), 10**k):
%o A397341             candidate = int(str(term) + str(p))
%o A397341             if sp.isprime(candidate):
%o A397341                 return p, candidate
%o A397341         k += 1
%o A397341 an = 1
%o A397341 a = [an]
%o A397341 for n in range(1, 18):
%o A397341     p, an = anext(an)
%o A397341     a.append(an)
%o A397341 print(a)
